Step-by-Step KIND Cluster Setup Guide
1. Install KIND and kubectl
Install KIND
bash
# Download and install KIND (Linux/macOS)
curl -Lo ./kind https://kind.sigs.k8s.io/dl/v0.20.0/kind-linux-amd64
chmod +x ./kind
sudo mv ./kind /usr/local/bin/kind

# Verify installation
kind --version
Install kubectl
bash
# Install kubectl (Linux)
curl -LO "https://dl.k8s.io/release/$(curl -L -s https://dl.k8s.io/release/stable.txt)/bin/linux/amd64/kubectl"
chmod +x kubectl
sudo mv kubectl /usr/local/bin/

# Verify installation
kubectl version --client
2. Create a KIND Cluster
Create a kind-config.yaml file
bash
cat <<EOF > kind-config.yaml
kind: Cluster
apiVersion: kind.x-k8s.io/v1alpha4
nodes:
  - role: control-plane
    image: kindest/node:v1.27.3  # Change version if needed
  - role: worker
    image: kindest/node:v1.27.3
  - role: worker
    image: kindest/node:v1.27.3
EOF
Create the Cluster
bash
kind create cluster --config kind-config.yaml --name my-kind-cluster
Verify the Cluster
bash
kubectl get nodes
kubectl cluster-info
3. Access the Cluster
Check Cluster Access
bash
kubectl get pods -A
4. Set Up Kubernetes Dashboard
Deploy the Dashboard
bash
kubectl apply -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/kubernetes/dashboard/v2.7.0/aio/deploy/recommended.yaml
Create an Admin User
bash
cat <<EOF > dashboard-admin-user.yml
apiVersion: v1
kind: ServiceAccount
metadata:
  name: admin-user
  namespace: kubernetes-dashboard
---
apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: ClusterRoleBinding
metadata:
  name: admin-user
roleRef:
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
  kind: ClusterRole
  name: cluster-admin
subjects:
- kind: ServiceAccount
  name: admin-user
  namespace: kubernetes-dashboard
EOF
Apply Admin User Configuration
bash
kubectl apply -f dashboard-admin-user.yml
Get the Access Token
bash
kubectl -n kubernetes-dashboard create token admin-user
Copy the token (you'll need it to log in).

Access the Dashboard
Start the proxy:

bash
kubectl proxy
Open the Dashboard in your browser:

text
http://localhost:8001/api/v1/namespaces/kubernetes-dashboard/services/https:kubernetes-dashboard:/proxy/
Log in using the token you copied earlier.

5. Delete the Cluster
bash
kind delete cluster --name my-kind-cluster
6. Notes
Multiple Clusters: Use different --name values to create multiple clusters.

Custom Kubernetes Version: Change image: kindest/node:v1.27.3 in kind-config.yaml.

Ephemeral Clusters: KIND clusters are temporary and will be lost if Docker restarts.
